      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e On Linux we\u0027ll be sending SIGTERM only to the luciexe process. On Windows we\u0027ll be sending Ctrl+C to the luciexe process and all its subprocesses (unless they start as a new process group). I think this will interfere with graceful termination of the subprocesses?\n\nYes, I\u0027m aware of that. Luckily, at least for recipe, we always launch subprocesses in new process group[1] so they shouldn\u0027t receive any signal sent from bbagent level. I plan to add a section to luciexe protocol spec for graceful termination and also requires that subprocesses MUST be launched in a new process group on Windows platform. Beyond that, I\u0027m not sure if there\u0027s anything else we can do.\n\n[1]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/infra/infra/+/master:recipes-py/recipe_engine/internal/step_runner/subproc.py;l\u003d47;drc\u003dff32fd7f9aa8328eb61ee5083611f9fb1112958a\n\n\n\u003e Another issue is that GenerateConsoleCtrlEvent is ignored if the process has no console attached. So this may mysteriously break later if we decided, for example, run Swarming bot via pythonw.exe (that has no console).\n\u003e \n\u003e But I don\u0027t know of a better way 🙈\n\nGood point! I don\u0027t know about that before. Though I think in that case, Swarming might face the same problem of how to terminate bbagent/kitchen (I\u0027ve assumed the current swarming implementation is based on GenerateConsoleCtrlEvent function as well). \n\nWindows Noob here, I\u0027m wondering if `CREATE_NEW_CONSOLE` creation flag would help here. i.e. bbagent could always create the subprocess in a new console and then whenever bbagent needs to terminate that subprocess, it create a new process and attach the process to the console where the to-be-terminated subprocess is running and call GenerateConsoleCtrlEvent.",
